{"schema":"algviz/1","title":"Kruskal's MST (sort + union-find)","topic":"graphs","code":["static int KruskalMst(int n, int[][] edges)","{","    Array.Sort(edges, (a, b) => a[2] - b[2]);","    var dsu = new DSU(n);","    int total = 0, used = 0;","    foreach (int[] e in edges)","    {","        if (dsu.Union(e[0], e[1]))","        {","            total += e[2];","            if (++used == n - 1) break;","        }","    }","    return total;","}"],"structures":{"edges":{"type":"array1d","label":"edges sorted by weight  (u-v:w)"},"g":{"type":"graph","label":"weighted graph (undirected)"},"parent":{"type":"array1d","label":"DSU parent[] (root points at itself)"}},"frames":[{"line":3,"caption":"Sort all edges by weight (already ascending here). Start with 5 singleton components — no edges chosen yet.","note":"A minimum spanning tree connects every vertex with V-1 edges of least total weight. Kruskal builds it by considering edges in increasing weight and keeping each one that does not form a cycle, using union-find to test \"same component?\" in near-constant time. The parent[] array IS the forest.","vars":{"total":0,"used":0},"result":null,"states":{"edges":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"0-1:1"},{"key":"c1","value":"1-2:2"},{"key":"c2","value":"0-2:3"},{"key":"c3","value":"1-3:4"},{"key":"c4","value":"2-4:5"},{"key":"c5","value":"3-4:6"}],"range":null},"g":{"type":"graph","directed":false,"nodes":[{"key":"0","value":0,"x":12,"y":50,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"1","value":1,"x":45,"y":16,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"2","value":2,"x":45,"y":84,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"3","value":3,"x":86,"y":26,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"4","value":4,"x":86,"y":74,"highlight":"current"}],"edges":[{"from":"0","to":"1","weight":1},{"from":"1","to":"2","weight":2},{"from":"0","to":"2","weight":3},{"from":"1","to":"3","weight":4},{"from":"2","to":"4","weight":5},{"from":"3","to":"4","weight":6}]},"parent":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":0,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":1,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c2","value":2,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c3","value":3,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c4","value":4,"highlight":"active"}],"range":null}}},{"line":8,"caption":"Consider edge 0-1 (w=1): find(0)=0, find(1)=1.","note":"Kruskal is the cut property applied globally: sort every edge by weight and consider them cheapest-first. The only question for each edge is whether its two endpoints already sit in the same union-find component. If they do, the edge would close a cycle and is useless; if not, it is the cheapest way to merge two pieces of the forest, so it is safe to take.","vars":{"total":0,"used":0,"edge":"0-1","w":1,"find(u)":0,"find(v)":1},"result":null,"states":{"edges":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"0-1:1","pointers":["e"],"highlight":"compared"},{"key":"c1","value":"1-2:2"},{"key":"c2","value":"0-2:3"},{"key":"c3","value":"1-3:4"},{"key":"c4","value":"2-4:5"},{"key":"c5","value":"3-4:6"}],"range":null},"g":{"type":"graph","directed":false,"nodes":[{"key":"0","value":0,"x":12,"y":50,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"1","value":1,"x":45,"y":16,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"2","value":2,"x":45,"y":84,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"3","value":3,"x":86,"y":26,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"4","value":4,"x":86,"y":74,"highlight":"current"}],"edges":[{"from":"0","to":"1","weight":1,"highlight":"compared"},{"from":"1","to":"2","weight":2},{"from":"0","to":"2","weight":3},{"from":"1","to":"3","weight":4},{"from":"2","to":"4","weight":5},{"from":"3","to":"4","weight":6}]},"parent":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":0,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":1,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c2","value":2,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c3","value":3,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c4","value":4,"highlight":"active"}],"range":null}}},{"line":10,"caption":"Roots differ → ADD 0-1. MST weight 1, 1 edge used.","note":"The endpoints have different roots, so this edge joins two separate trees of the forest without making a cycle — Union returns true. We add its weight to the MST total and merge the components. Because we always take the lightest cycle-free edge available, the cut property guarantees the result is a minimum spanning tree. We stop the moment we have V-1 edges: that many edges with no cycle is exactly a spanning tree.","vars":{"total":1,"used":1,"edge":"0-1","w":1,"find(u)":0,"find(v)":1},"result":null,"states":{"edges":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"0-1:1","pointers":["e"],"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c1","value":"1-2:2"},{"key":"c2","value":"0-2:3"},{"key":"c3","value":"1-3:4"},{"key":"c4","value":"2-4:5"},{"key":"c5","value":"3-4:6"}],"range":null},"g":{"type":"graph","directed":false,"nodes":[{"key":"0","value":0,"x":12,"y":50,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"1","value":1,"x":45,"y":16,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"2","value":2,"x":45,"y":84,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"3","value":3,"x":86,"y":26,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"4","value":4,"x":86,"y":74,"highlight":"match"}],"edges":[{"from":"0","to":"1","weight":1,"highlight":"path"},{"from":"1","to":"2","weight":2},{"from":"0","to":"2","weight":3},{"from":"1","to":"3","weight":4},{"from":"2","to":"4","weight":5},{"from":"3","to":"4","weight":6}]},"parent":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":0,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c2","value":2,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c3","value":3,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c4","value":4,"highlight":"active"}],"range":null}}},{"line":8,"caption":"Consider edge 1-2 (w=2): find(1)=0, find(2)=2.","note":"Kruskal is the cut property applied globally: sort every edge by weight and consider them cheapest-first. The only question for each edge is whether its two endpoints already sit in the same union-find component. If they do, the edge would close a cycle and is useless; if not, it is the cheapest way to merge two pieces of the forest, so it is safe to take.","vars":{"total":1,"used"